{{efn | name = on battleships and armoured cruisers | [[Pre-dreadnought|Battleships]] of the day carried heavy armor and a main battery of four large-caliber guns, typically 11&nbsp;in (280&nbsp;mm) or larger. [[Armored cruisers]] were smaller, faster ships that carried a thinner armored belt and smaller guns. }}
{{efn | name = two power standard | Britain had committed to building a navy that was larger than the next two closest rivals combined. See: {{harvnb|Gardiner & Gray|p=134}}. }}
{{efn | name = coal quality | Due to the wartime situation, Germany had limited access to high quality coal, but was able to acquire lower-grade coal for its ships. The higher quality coal was generally reserved for the smaller craft, whose crews were less able to clean the boilers at the increased rate demanded by the low-quality coal. As a result, German capital ships were often supplied with poor coal, in the knowledge that their larger crews were better able to perform the increased maintenance. After 1915, the practice of spraying oil onto the low-quality coal was introduced, in order to increase the burn rate. See: {{harvnb|Philbin|p=56}}. }}
{{efn | name = wing turrets | The contemporary British dreadnoughts carried three of their five turrets on the centerline of the ship, while the other two were on the "wings". American and Japanese dreadnoughts carried all of their guns on the centerline. }}
{{efn | name = gun nomenclature | In Imperial German Navy gun nomenclature, "SK" (Schnelladekanone) denotes that the gun quick firing, while the L/45 denotes the length of the gun. In this case, the L/45 gun is 45 [[Caliber (artillery)|caliber]], meaning that the gun is 45 as times long as it is in diameter. }}
{{efn | name = provisional names | The German navy orders a ship under a provisional name that indicates which obsolete unit of the fleet the new ship will replace. Upon completion, the ship is christened with the intended name. In this case, ''Ersatz Bayern'' was intended to replace {{SMS|Bayern|1878|6}}, and once the ship was finished, she was christened ''Nassau''. }}
}}
